{
  "cert_id": "iso27001_li",
  "domain_id": "annex_a_controls",
  "quiz_num": 3,
  "domain_name": "Controles Anexo A — ISO 27002",
  "cert_name": "ISO 27001 Lead Implementer",
  "lang": "en",
  "questions": [
    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022, which of the following best describes the purpose of conducting a risk assessment in an information security management system (ISMS)?",
      "tag": "Risk Assessment & Treatment",
      "options": [
        "B. To eliminate all information security risks completely from the organization",
        "D. To comply with regulatory requirements without affecting business operations",
        "C. To assign financial budgets exclusively to high-risk areas",
        "A. To identify, analyze, and evaluate information security risks to determine appropriate treatment strategies"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1 requires organizations to determine and analyze information security risks through systematic processes. Risk assessment identifies threats, vulnerabilities, and impacts to establish treatment plans, forming the foundation of ISMS.",
      "justification_wrong": "Complete risk elimination is impossible; budget assignment and regulatory compliance alone do not constitute proper risk assessment methodology per ISO 27001:2022 requirements."
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "Which ISO 27002:2022 control category addresses the protection of physical facilities and equipment from unauthorized access and environmental damage?",
      "tag": "Physical Controls",
      "options": [
        "D. Technological controls managing cryptographic mechanisms",
        "A. Organizational controls focusing on governance frameworks",
        "B. People controls targeting awareness and competence",
        "C. Physical controls including perimeter security and environmental protection"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Physical Controls (14 controls) cover facility perimeter, entry points, monitoring, and environmental management. These prevent unauthorized physical access and protect assets from environmental threats per Clauses 7.1-7.14.",
      "justification_wrong": "Organizational controls address governance; people controls focus on competence; technological controls manage IT systems. Physical controls specifically address tangible infrastructure protection."
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "Under ISO 27001:2022, what is the primary responsibility of top management regarding the ISMS?",
      "tag": "Leadership & Governance",
      "options": [
        "B. Demonstrate leadership and commitment by establishing context, objectives, and supporting implementation",
        "A. Delegate all ISMS responsibilities to the Information Security Officer without oversight",
        "D. Review ISMS annually only when auditors request documentation",
        "C. Focus exclusively on technical security controls and ignore organizational aspects"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 5.1 mandates top management to demonstrate commitment, establish organizational context, define information security objectives, and provide necessary resources and support for ISMS effectiveness.",
      "justification_wrong": "Delegation without oversight, technical-only focus, and reactive auditing contradict ISO 27001:2022 leadership requirements emphasizing continuous commitment and integration within organizational strategy."
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "text": "According to ISO 27002:2022, which control ensures that individuals understand their information security responsibilities and maintain competence?",
      "tag": "People Controls - Awareness & Competence",
      "options": [
        "A. Access control and cryptographic key management",
        "C. Physical perimeter protection and visitor management",
        "D. Incident response procedures and business continuity planning",
        "B. Information security awareness, education, and training programs"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Clause 6.2 (People controls) requires organizations to implement awareness programs and provide training to ensure personnel understand security policies and maintain appropriate competence levels throughout their employment.",
      "justification_wrong": "Access control, physical protection, and incident response are distinct control categories not specifically addressing awareness and competence development per ISO 27002:2022 People controls theme."
    },
    {
      "num": 5,
      "text": "Which of the following represents the correct approach for selecting information security controls according to ISO 27001:2022?",
      "tag": "Control Selection & Implementation",
      "options": [
        "C. Select controls solely based on industry benchmarks without considering specific organizational risks",
        "A. Implement all 93 ISO 27002:2022 controls regardless of organizational context and risk assessment results",
        "D. Defer control implementation until after the certification audit is scheduled",
        "B. Implement controls based on risk assessment results, organizational context, and legal/regulatory requirements"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.2 requires control selection based on risk assessment outcomes, organizational context, legal obligations, and stakeholder requirements. This ensures relevance, proportionality, and cost-effectiveness of implemented controls.",
      "justification_wrong": "Implementing all controls indiscriminately, benchmarking-only approaches, and deferred implementation violate ISO 27001:2022 principles of risk-based control selection and demonstrated ISMS establishment."
    },
    {
      "num": 6,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022, which of the following best describes the primary purpose of establishing an Information Security Management System (ISMS)?",
      "tag": "ISMS Fundamentals",
      "options": [
        "A. To establish a systematic approach to manage and protect information assets through risk-based controls and continuous improvement",
        "C. To comply solely with regulatory requirements without considering organizational objectives",
        "B. To exclusively implement technical security controls and encryption mechanisms",
        "D. To eliminate all information security risks completely"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 4.1-4.3 emphasizes ISMS as a risk-based, systematic approach integrating organizational, people, physical, and technological controls with continuous improvement cycles.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options B, C, D misrepresent ISMS scope. Technical controls alone are insufficient (Clause 5). Regulation compliance is secondary to risk management. Complete risk elimination is impossible."
    },
    {
      "num": 7,
      "text": "In ISO 27001:2022, which control domain contains the requirement for 'Personnel screening' and 'Confidentiality or non-disclosure agreements'?",
      "tag": "Controls Classification - People Domain",
      "options": [
        "C. Physical controls (A.7 Physical controls)",
        "B. People controls (A.6 People controls)",
        "A. Organizational controls (A.5 Organizational controls)",
        "D. Technological controls (A.8 Technological controls)"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Annex A, Section A.6 (People controls) encompasses controls 6.1-6.8, including personnel screening (6.2) and confidentiality agreements (6.3) for workforce management.",
      "justification_wrong": "Screening and agreements are human resources matters. Organizational (A.5) focuses on policies/governance; Physical (A.7) on premises; Technological (A.8) on systems."
    },
    {
      "num": 8,
      "text": "Which statement correctly reflects ISO 27001:2022 requirements regarding the scope and boundaries of an ISMS?",
      "tag": "ISMS Scope Definition",
      "options": [
        "C. Scope determination is mandatory only for organizations with more than 500 employees",
        "B. Scope is determined by the organization considering its context, stakeholders, and relevant information assets",
        "A. Scope must include all organizational departments regardless of information criticality or relevance",
        "D. Scope cannot be modified once initially defined during ISMS implementation"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 4.3 requires organizations to define ISMS scope based on context (4.1), stakeholder needs, and information asset relevance, enabling flexible boundary setting.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A: overinclusion reduces effectiveness. Option C: size-independent requirement. Option D: scope evolves with organizational context changes (Clause 4.4 - periodic review)."
    },
    {
      "num": 9,
      "text": "According to ISO 27002:2022, control A.5.1 'Policies for information security' requires that information security policies should be:",
      "tag": "Organizational Controls - Policy Framework",
      "options": [
        "D. Documented in a single comprehensive document covering all technical requirements",
        "C. Implemented only for critical information assets identified in risk assessment",
        "B. Approved by appropriate management, communicated to relevant personnel, and reviewed periodically",
        "A. Approved by IT department only and reviewed annually by technical staff"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 A.5.1 guidance states policies require management approval, organization-wide communication, periodic reviews, and accessibility to relevant stakeholders.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A: excludes senior management approval. Option C: all information requires policy coverage. Option D: modular documentation is preferred for maintainability."
    },
    {
      "num": 10,
      "text": "In ISO 27001:2022, the relationship between risk assessment (Clause 6.1.2) and risk treatment (Clause 6.1.3) demonstrates which key principle?",
      "tag": "Risk Management Cycle",
      "options": [
        "A. Risk assessment must be completed before any treatment decisions, ensuring informed control selection",
        "C. Risk assessment is optional if organization has pre-existing controls already implemented",
        "B. Risk treatment and risk assessment can occur independently without documented relationship",
        "D. Risk treatment decisions are determined solely by regulatory compliance requirements"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1.2-6.1.3 establishes sequential logic: assessment identifies risks, treatment selects controls. Clause 8.1 requires documented risk treatment plan derived from assessment.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B: violates risk-based approach. Option C: assessment is mandatory (Clause 6.1). Option D: risk-based decisions precede compliance mapping (Clause 6.2)."
    },
    {
      "num": 11,
      "text": "According to ISO/IEC 27001:2022 and ISO/IEC 27002:2022, which control from the Organizational theme directly addresses the requirement to establish and maintain an information security policy framework?",
      "tag": "Policy Framework & Governance",
      "options": [
        "C. Control 8.1 - Physical perimeter",
        "D. Control 5.23 - Information security for supplier relationships",
        "A. Control 5.1 - Policies for information security",
        "B. Control 6.1 - Screening"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Control 5.1 explicitly requires organizations to establish comprehensive information security policies covering scope, objectives, roles, and responsibilities. It forms the foundation for the entire ISMS per ISO 27001:2022 clause 5.2.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 6.1 addresses personnel screening; 8.1 covers physical access; 5.23 focuses on supplier relationships. None establish the overarching policy framework required by the standard's foundational requirements."
    },
    {
      "num": 12,
      "text": "In the context of ISO/IEC 27002:2022 People controls, what is the primary objective of control 6.2 (Information security awareness, education and training)?",
      "tag": "Personnel Security & Awareness",
      "options": [
        "D. To document only compliance violations for audit purposes",
        "B. To ensure all personnel understand their security responsibilities and develop competence in information security practices",
        "A. To punish employees who violate security policies",
        "C. To replace the need for technical security controls"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Control 6.2 mandates awareness and training programs ensuring personnel comprehend security policies, roles, and responsibilities. It develops organizational competence and reduces human-centric risks per ISO 27002:2022 guidance.",
      "justification_wrong": "Awareness programs aim to prevent violations, not punish them (A). Technical controls remain essential (C). Documentation extends beyond violations to demonstrate competency building (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 13,
      "text": "Which Physical controls from ISO/IEC 27002:2022 must work in combination to protect information assets in data centers from unauthorized access and environmental threats?",
      "tag": "Physical & Environmental Security",
      "options": [
        "A. Controls 7.1 (Physical perimeters) and 7.2 (Physical entry) only",
        "C. Controls 7.4 (Monitoring) and 7.14 (Secure disposal) exclusively",
        "D. Control 7.13 (Utility supplies) alone is sufficient",
        "B. Controls 7.1, 7.2, 7.3 (Securing offices, rooms and facilities) and 7.12 (Cabling security)"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Comprehensive physical protection requires layered controls: perimeters (7.1), access control (7.2), facility security (7.3), and infrastructure integrity (7.12). Combined approach addresses access, environmental, and infrastructure risks per ISO 27002:2022.",
      "justification_wrong": "Single controls (A, C, D) provide incomplete protection. Effective data center security demands multi-layered defense including boundary, entry, workspace, and cable protections simultaneously."
    },
    {
      "num": 14,
      "text": "According to ISO/IEC 27002:2022 Technological controls, control 8.10 (Separation of development, test and production environments) is critical for which primary reason?",
      "tag": "System & Communications Security",
      "options": [
        "C. To eliminate the need for change management processes",
        "D. To simplify user access management across all environments",
        "A. To reduce hardware costs across development stages",
        "B. To prevent malicious code or configuration errors in development from impacting production systems and live data"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Environment separation prevents development/test risks from compromising production integrity and live data. ISO 27002:2022 emphasizes isolation to contain errors and limit attack surface exposure in operational systems.",
      "justification_wrong": "Cost reduction (A) is secondary benefit. Separation complements, not replaces change management (C). Access management must be stringent across all environments, not simplified (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 15,
      "text": "In implementing ISO/IEC 27001:2022 clause 8.2 (Determine the scope of the ISMS), which organizational factors must be explicitly documented to establish proper ISMS boundaries?",
      "tag": "ISMS Scope & Implementation",
      "options": [
        "D. Regulatory compliance costs and third-party audit fees",
        "B. External context, internal context, relevant interested parties, and organizational objectives related to information security",
        "C. Number of employees and office locations exclusively",
        "A. Budget allocation and IT department size only"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 8.2 requires documented scope reflecting organizational context (external, internal), stakeholder needs, and security objectives. These elements determine ISMS applicability and control selection per normative requirements.",
      "justification_wrong": "Budget/size (A) don't define scope adequacy. Employee count/locations (C) are insufficient for comprehensive boundary determination. Audit costs (D) are operational considerations, not scope-defining factors."
    },
    {
      "num": 16,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022 and ISO 27002:2022, which control category addresses the requirement to implement technical measures for detecting unauthorized access to information systems?",
      "tag": "Technological Controls - Access Control",
      "options": [
        "A. Access control and cryptography (ISO 27002: 5.15-5.16)",
        "C. Personnel security procedures (ISO 27002: 6.1-6.8)",
        "B. Physical security measures only (ISO 27002: 7.1-7.3)",
        "D. Organizational governance frameworks (ISO 27002: 5.1-5.5)"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Section 5 (Technological Controls) explicitly covers access control and cryptography (5.15-5.16), including detection mechanisms. These are mandatory controls for unauthorized access detection per normative requirements.",
      "justification_wrong": "Physical, personnel, and organizational controls support but do not directly address technical detection of unauthorized access as required by ISO 27001:2022 Annex A."
    },
    {
      "num": 17,
      "text": "When implementing ISO 27001:2022, an organization must conduct a risk assessment. Which statement correctly reflects the relationship between risk assessment and control selection per ISO 27002:2022?",
      "tag": "Risk Management - Control Selection",
      "options": [
        "A. Risk assessment determines which ISO 27002 controls to implement based on organizational context (ISO 27001: 6.1.1-6.1.3)",
        "C. Risk assessment is optional for organizations with fewer than 50 employees",
        "B. All 93 ISO 27002 controls must be implemented regardless of risk assessment results",
        "D. Control selection is predetermined by industry sector, not risk assessment"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 6.1.1-6.1.3 requires risk assessment to determine context and identify information security risks. Control selection from ISO 27002 follows this assessment. This is fundamental to the risk-based approach.",
      "justification_wrong": "ISO 27001 mandates risk assessment for all organizations. Clause 6.1 explicitly states risk assessment informs control implementation, not predetermined selection or universal application."
    },
    {
      "num": 18,
      "text": "ISO 27002:2022 categorizes controls into four themes. An organization implements employee confidentiality agreements and background check procedures. Which theme classification applies?",
      "tag": "Control Themes - People Controls",
      "options": [
        "B. Organizational (Theme 1: 5.1-5.37) - Governance and policy controls",
        "A. People (Theme 2: 6.1-6.8) - Personnel security and screening controls",
        "C. Technological (Theme 4: 8.1-8.34) - Technical implementation controls",
        "D. Physical (Theme 3: 7.1-7.14) - Environmental protection controls"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Theme 2 (People Controls, 6.1-6.8) explicitly covers personnel screening, background verification, and confidentiality agreements per normative structure.",
      "justification_wrong": "Organizational controls address policies/governance, technological controls address systems/cryptography, and physical controls address premises access—none directly address personnel screening."
    },
    {
      "num": 19,
      "text": "During an ISO 27001:2022 audit, an examiner verifies that the organization has implemented encryption for sensitive data at rest. Which ISO 27002:2022 control reference is most relevant?",
      "tag": "Cryptography - Data Protection",
      "options": [
        "A. Control 5.16 (Encryption) - Cryptographic controls for data protection (ISO 27002: 5.16)",
        "D. Control 6.5 (Access rights review) - User permission audits",
        "C. Control 7.1 (Physical security perimeter) - Building access controls",
        "B. Control 5.1 (Policies for information security) - General policy framework"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 control 5.16 specifically addresses encryption and cryptographic mechanisms for protecting data confidentiality and integrity at rest and in transit. This is the normative technical control.",
      "justification_wrong": "Controls 5.1, 7.1, and 6.5 address policies, physical access, and permissions respectively—not cryptographic implementation for data protection as required."
    },
    {
      "num": 20,
      "text": "An organization implements a control to ensure that all personnel receive mandatory annual information security awareness training. Under ISO 27002:2022, which theme and control number applies?",
      "tag": "People Controls - Security Awareness",
      "options": [
        "D. Theme 3 (Physical), Control 7.2 - Physical access training requirements",
        "B. Theme 1 (Organizational), Control 5.2 - Information security roles and responsibilities",
        "C. Theme 4 (Technological), Control 8.3 - Technical security awareness programs",
        "A. Theme 2 (People), Control 6.2 - Information security awareness, education, and training (ISO 27002: 6.2)"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Theme 2 (People), Control 6.2 explicitly mandates information security awareness and training programs for all personnel. This is the normative requirement for awareness activities.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 5.2 addresses roles/responsibilities, 8.3 is technical (not organizational awareness), and 7.2 covers physical access—none directly address security awareness training as control 6.2 does."
    },
    {
      "num": 21,
      "text": "According to ISO/IEC 27001:2022 and ISO/IEC 27002:2022, when establishing an Information Security Management System (ISMS), which organizational control is fundamental to ensure accountability and proper governance?",
      "tag": "Organizational Controls - Governance",
      "options": [
        "D. Delegation of all security decisions to the external auditor",
        "A. Establishment of information security roles and responsibilities with clear segregation of duties",
        "B. Implementation of only technical controls to prevent all security incidents",
        "C. Annual review of the ISMS without documentation requirements"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 5.1 requires organizations to establish roles and responsibilities. ISO 27002:2022 control 5.1 emphasizes governance structure. Clear accountability ensures effective security management and supports Clause 6.1 (risk assessment) and 6.2 (risk treatment).",
      "justification_wrong": "Technical controls alone cannot ensure governance (B). Annual reviews without documentation violate Clause 6.3 requirements (C). External auditors provide assurance but cannot make organizational decisions (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 22,
      "text": "In the context of ISO/IEC 27002:2022 People controls, what is the primary objective of implementing supplier/third-party information security management?",
      "tag": "People Controls - Third-Party Management",
      "options": [
        "C. To eliminate the need for internal security policies by outsourcing all controls",
        "A. To transfer all security responsibility to suppliers regardless of contractual terms",
        "B. To establish and maintain information security requirements throughout the supplier lifecycle, including assessment, agreements, and monitoring",
        "D. To reduce audit costs by having suppliers conduct independent assessments only"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 control 6.8 requires supplier management throughout the entire lifecycle. ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.1 mandates documented information security requirements for external parties. This ensures consistent security across the organization's value chain.",
      "justification_wrong": "Responsibility cannot be completely transferred (A). Internal policies remain mandatory regardless of outsourcing (C). Regular monitoring is required, not just independent assessments (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 23,
      "text": "Under ISO/IEC 27001:2022 Clause 6 (Planning) and ISO/IEC 27002:2022 organizational controls, how should an organization address identified information security risks that exceed the risk appetite?",
      "tag": "Organizational Controls - Risk Treatment",
      "options": [
        "D. Defer all risk treatment decisions until the next annual audit",
        "A. Accept all risks to minimize implementation costs and avoid control complexity",
        "B. Implement risk treatment plans through control selection, implementation, and verification as defined in Clause 6.2",
        "C. Ignore risks above the risk appetite as they are statistically unlikely to occur"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.2 requires organizations to select and implement controls based on risk assessment outcomes. Risk treatment must be documented in Statement of Applicability (SoA). This ensures systematic risk management aligned with organizational context and risk appetite.",
      "justification_wrong": "Risk acceptance must be justified and documented (A). Ignoring identified risks violates duty of care (C). Risk treatment cannot be deferred; timely action is required per Clause 6.2 (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 24,
      "text": "Regarding ISO/IEC 27002:2022 Physical and Environmental controls, which approach best demonstrates compliance with the requirement to protect information systems from physical threats?",
      "tag": "Physical Controls - Asset Protection",
      "options": [
        "D. Relying exclusively on cybersecurity controls without physical safeguards",
        "B. Installing only surveillance cameras as the sole physical security measure",
        "C. Restricting all employee access without considering operational requirements",
        "A. Implementing perimeter security, access controls, surveillance systems, and environmental protections documented in the ISMS"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 controls 7.1-7.14 address physical security comprehensively: perimeter controls (7.1), access control (7.2), surveillance (7.4), and environmental controls (7.10-7.14). Integrated approach ensures defense-in-depth aligned with Clause 8.3 (implementation guidance).",
      "justification_wrong": "Cameras alone are insufficient (B). Overly restrictive access impairs operations (C). Physical and cyber controls are complementary, both essential per ISO 27001 holistic approach (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 25,
      "text": "In ISO/IEC 27002:2022 Technological controls, how should an organization implement cryptographic controls to ensure information confidentiality and integrity across its IT infrastructure?",
      "tag": "Technological Controls - Cryptography",
      "options": [
        "C. Encrypt all data uniformly without considering classification levels or risk profiles",
        "A. Apply encryption selectively to non-critical systems using outdated algorithms to reduce complexity",
        "D. Rely on vendor-default encryption settings without organizational policy or governance",
        "B. Establish a cryptographic policy defining key management, algorithm standards, and application based on risk assessment per controls 8.24-8.26"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 controls 8.24 (cryptographic controls), 8.25 (key management), and 8.26 (key generation) require documented policy aligned with information classification and risk assessment. This ensures proportionate, effective protection per ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.3 implementation requirements.",
      "justification_wrong": "Selective encryption with weak algorithms creates vulnerabilities (A). Uniform encryption ignores risk-based approach and is inefficient (C). Default settings lack organizational governance and accountability (D)."
    },
    {
      "num": 26,
      "text": "During an ISO 27001:2022 implementation, you discover that the organization's risk assessment process does not explicitly document the rationale for risk acceptance decisions. According to Clause 6.1.3 and A.5.1, what is the primary risk management implication?",
      "tag": "Risk Assessment & Treatment",
      "options": [
        "A. Risk acceptance decisions lack auditability and traceability, preventing demonstration of informed decision-making to stakeholders and auditors",
        "B. The organization must immediately implement encryption for all data to compensate for missing documentation",
        "D. Undocumented risk acceptance automatically triggers mandatory incident response procedures",
        "C. Risk acceptance is invalid unless approved by external auditors before implementation"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 6.1.3 requires documented risk treatment decisions. Without documented rationale, acceptance decisions cannot be reviewed, justified, or demonstrated as meeting organizational risk criteria per A.5.1, compromising governance and audit compliance.",
      "justification_wrong": "Encryption (B) is not a compensating control for missing documentation. External auditor approval (C) is not required pre-implementation. Risk acceptance (D) doesn't automatically trigger incident response."
    },
    {
      "num": 27,
      "text": "An organization implementing A.5.16 (Change Management) discovers that security patch deployment processes bypass the formal change control procedure during critical incidents. Which ISO 27001:2022 requirement is most directly violated?",
      "tag": "Change Management Controls",
      "options": [
        "A. Clause 8.1 (Operational Planning & Control) and A.5.16 mandate that changes, including emergency patches, must be authorized, documented, and reviewed before implementation",
        "C. Only configuration management systems can document patches; manual change logs are non-compliant",
        "D. Change management applies only to infrastructure; security patches follow a separate regulatory framework",
        "B. Emergency patches are exempt from change control under ISO 27001:2022 if approved verbally by IT leadership"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 8.1 and A.5.16 require all changes, including emergency ones, be evaluated, authorized, documented, and reviewed. Emergency procedures must still include documented approval and post-implementation verification to maintain control integrity.",
      "justification_wrong": "Verbal approval (B) contradicts written documentation requirement. Configuration systems (C) are tools, not mandatory. Patches (D) are organizational changes subject to A.5.16 controls."
    },
    {
      "num": 28,
      "text": "During internal audit of A.7.1 (Physical Security Perimeters), inspectors find that visitor access logs lack timestamps and visitor identification linking. Per Clause 7.2 and A.7.1, what is the control effectiveness issue?",
      "tag": "Physical Access Control",
      "options": [
        "B. Visitor logs are advisory only; timestamps are optional under ISO 27001:2022 if entry/exit gates are electronically monitored",
        "C. Missing identification requires purchase of biometric systems; no alternative compliance method exists",
        "A. Audit trail completeness is compromised; inability to correlate specific individuals with access events prevents forensic investigation and accountability verification",
        "D. Timestamps are redundant if visitor duration does not exceed 4 hours per organizational policy"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 7.2 and A.7.1 require physical access control with accountability mechanisms. Timestamps and identification enable forensic traceability. Without them, unauthorized access attribution is impossible, violating non-repudiation and monitoring objectives.",
      "justification_wrong": "Timestamps (B) are mandatory for accountability, not optional. Biometric systems (C) are one option; manual logs with timestamps are compliant. Duration (D) doesn't eliminate timestamp requirements."
    },
    {
      "num": 29,
      "text": "An organization implements A.8.3 (Segregation of Duties) by restricting developers from deploying code to production. However, developers retain admin credentials for UAT environments where production data copies exist. What is the primary control weakness per Clause 8.2 and A.8.3?",
      "tag": "Access Control & Segregation",
      "options": [
        "B. Segregation of duties applies only to production environments; UAT is exempt under ISO 27001:2022 regardless of data classification",
        "D. Segregation violations require immediate credential revocation; temporary access for testing is non-compliant in all scenarios",
        "A. Admin access to UAT containing production data effectively circumvents segregation intent; developers can alter data/logs before audit, defeating accountability and integrity objectives",
        "C. Restricting deployment authority is sufficient; additional access controls for UAT are redundant if developers lack production credentials"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 8.2 and A.8.3 require functional segregation of duties to prevent unauthorized/undetected actions. UAT with production data poses same risks; admin access enables data/log manipulation, undermining detective controls and auditability regardless of environment.",
      "justification_wrong": "UAT (B) is in-scope if it contains sensitive data. Admin UAT access (C) is not redundant. Segregation (D) requires design review, not automatic revocation; temporary controlled access may be compliant."
    },
    {
      "num": 30,
      "text": "During information classification review per A.2.1, the organization discovers 15% of sensitive data lacks assigned ownership or retention schedules. According to Clause 5.3 (Information & Cybersecurity Resource Roles) and A.2.1, what governance action is required?",
      "tag": "Information Classification & Ownership",
      "options": [
        "B. Unclassified data can remain in systems for up to 2 years pending budget approval for classification tools",
